title: For Sale:  Saint-Gauden Double Eagle Gold Coin
postcontent: For sale is a very nice 2008 Saint Gauden one ounce gold coin.  It is in excellant condition.The Saint-Gaudens double eagle is a twenty-dollar gold coin, or double eagle, produced by the United States Mint from 1907 to 1933. The coin is named after its designer, the sculptor Augustus Saint-Gaudens, who designed the obverse and reverse. It is considered by many to be the most beautiful of U.S. coins. In 1904, President Theodore Roosevelt sought to beautify American coinage, and proposed Saint-Gaudens as an artist capable of the task. Although the sculptor had poor experiences with the Mint and its chief engraver, Charles E. Barber, Saint-Gaudens accepted Roosevelt's call. The work was subject to considerable delays, due to Saint-Gaudens's declining health and difficulties because of the high relief of his design. Saint-Gaudens died in 1907, after designing the eagle and double eagle, but before the designs were finalized for production. After several versions of the design for the double eagle proved too difficult to strike, Barber modified Saint-Gaudens's design, lowering the relief so the coin could be struck with only one blow. When the coins were finally released, they proved controversial as they lacked the words "In God We Trust", and Congress intervened to require the motto's use. The coin was minted, primarily for use in international trade, until 1933. The 1933 double eagle is among the most valuable of U.S. coins, with the sole example currently known to be in private hands selling in 2002 for $7,590,020.Cash is obo and highly prefered but limited trades would include:Wilson Combat Tactical ShotgunBlack Rain AR in 223Quality side by side with cash from meMorgans or Peace Dollars?????

title: For Trade:  Scar 17s Limited Trial Run
location: Raliegh/Garner/Smithfield, Raleigh / Durham / CH, North Carolina
postcontent: In 2010, FN decided to bring the Scar 17s to the civilian market. They made these as limited inital production models. They made limited 16s and 17s. Limited 16s have 7 digit serial numbers, that is how many they produced. The 17s only have 3 digit serial numbers. These are incredibly rare. Mostly only dealers and company heads got their hands on these and still have most of them. I have never seen another come up for sale nor has the few big appraisors I had look at it. They came in a rolling Hardigg Storm case, 2 mags, and a Certificate of Authenticity. The intial production run was the test trial to see how well they would do. Only these were produced at a plant in the US. The same plant they made the ones for the military. After the initial production was released, all production moved to Belgium. So very few of them were made that when I called FN, they could not give me a exact number of how many were sold to the public. This is gun 186 out of all made. You won't see another much less one for sale. If you are lucky to see another one... it will be shot. Not brand new. Even has all the tags still on it. This is a great collectors item so dont miss it. Shoot me an offer. No I will not sell for the price of a new one that comes in a cardboard box and one mag that they made a million of. I know what its worth. Or close enough at least. Any other info email me and ill answer to the best of my knowledge. I have had several offers so just email me your best offer. Hard to start somewhere when theres no record of one being sold or for sale.
